I am about halfway through=C2=A0Going Infinite, Michael Lewis=E2=80=99 book=
 about Sam Bankman-Fried, and I am very much enjoying it.  Many of the  rev=
iews that I have read of the book complain that Lewis does not sufficiently=
 explain that Bankman-Fried is Guilty and Bad, Actually, but that is not th=
e book that he wanted to write or the one I want to read.
  [1]
 He wanted to understand and explain Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s psychology and=
 tell a good story. If you want to read a moral condemnation of crypto thef=
t, you can get that=C2=A0anywhere.=C2=A0You go to Michael Lewis for charact=
er and=C2=A0story.
Also, reading those reviews you would think that the book is a defense of B=
ankman-Fried, but it is actually quite damning. (Less=C2=A0damning than mos=
t of what is written about Bankman-Fried these days? Sure.) There is an ane=
cdote (which has been reported before) from the early days of Alameda Resea=
rch, the crypto trading firm that Bankman-Fried started before his crypto e=
xchange FTX, the firm whose trades with FTX customer money ultimately broug=
ht down the whole thing. At some point Alameda lost track of $4 million of =
investor money, and the rest of the management team was like =E2=80=9Chuh w=
e should tell our investors that we lost their money,=E2=80=9D and Bankman-=
Fried was like =E2=80=9Cnah it=E2=80=99s fine, we=E2=80=99ll probably find =
it again, let=E2=80=99s just tell them it=E2=80=99s still here.=E2=80=9D Th=
e rest of the management team was horrified and quit in a huff, loudly tell=
ing the investors that Bankman-Fried was dishonest and reckless.
And then Alameda eventually=C2=A0did=C2=A0find the money and it was fine. T=
he lesson that Bankman-Fried, and everyone else who stayed at Alameda, seem=
s to have taken from this episode was something like =E2=80=9CBankman-Fried=
 is infallible, and it=E2=80=99s fine if he takes wild risks and does fraud=
 because it always=C2=A0works out in the end.=E2=80=9D I wonder how that ap=
proach will play out in the second half of the book!
There is another strange anecdote from Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s even earlier=
 days, as an intern at Jane Street Capital, the proprietary trading firm.
  [2]
=C2=A0Jane Street wants to teach its interns to think in bets, so they are =
encouraged to bet against each other all the time. To prevent disaster, the=
re is a rule=C2=A0that no intern can lose more than $100 in a day.
  [3]
=C2=A0One morning,=C2=A0another intern, called =E2=80=9CAsher=E2=80=9D in t=
he book,=C2=A0offers to bet Bankman-Fried on the maximum amount any intern =
will lose that day. =E2=80=9CThis cannot settle above one hundred or below =
zero, right?=E2=80=9D confirms Bankman-Fried. And then he buys at 65: If an=
y intern loses more than $65 that day, Bankman-Fried will pay Asher that in=
tern=E2=80=99s losses above $65; if none do, Asher will pay Bankman-Fried t=
he difference between $65 and the maximum loss. If an intern loses $100, th=
e maximum, then=C2=A0Bankman-Fried gets $35. If the biggest loser loses onl=
y=C2=A0$50, he pays Asher $15.
Of course Bankman-Fried can easily win this bet by=C2=A0losing $100 himself=
. That is not optimal, for him, but he can use that fact to manufacture a g=
ood trade. He immediately turns to the other interns in the room and offers=
 them $1 to take an even-money coin flip for $98.=C2=A0Somebody (Bankman-Fr=
ied or his counterparty) will lose $98 on this bet, so Asher will have to p=
ay him $33 ($98 minus $65).=C2=A0If Bankman-Fried=C2=A0wins, he gets $98 (f=
rom winning the coin flip), plus $33 (from Asher), minus $1 (he paid the ot=
her intern a premium to do the coin flip), for a net gain of $130.
  [4]
=C2=A0If he loses, he loses $98 (coin flip) plus $1 (payment) but gets back=
 $33 (Asher), for a net loss of $66.
  [5]
 That=E2=80=99s a very positive-expected-value bet for him: Bankman-Fried h=
as a 50/50 chance of winning $130 or losing only $66. But it=E2=80=99s also=
 positive-expected-value for his counterparty on the coin flip.=C2=A0Lewis =
writes:
To the Jane Street way of thinking, Sam was offering free money. A Jane Str=
eet intern had what amounted to a professional obligation to take any bet w=
ith a positive expected value. The coin toss itself was a 50-50 proposition=
, and so the expected value to the person who accepted Sam=E2=80=99s bet wa=
s a dollar: (0.5 x $98) - (0.5 x $98) + $1 =3D $1.
Bankman-Fried easily saw how to=C2=A0manufacture=C2=A0the bad outcome for A=
sher. This is a key skill in trading, but especially in crypto trading. =E2=
=80=9CAsher was now clearly deeply embarrassed.=E2=80=9D
Bankman-Fried finds a taker,=C2=A0wins the coin toss and collects $98 from =
the other intern. Then he goes again:

To maximize Asher=E2=80=99s pain, some intern needed to lose one hundred do=
llars.
I=E2=80=99ll pay a dollar to anyone who will flip me for ninety-nine dollar=
s, Sam shouted.
Now he had a machine for creating wagers in which both parties enjoyed posi=
tive expected value. That machine was named Asher. Interns were lined up to=
 take the bet. =E2=80=9CPeople get so obsessed with free dollars when you f=
rame it correctly,=E2=80=9D said Sam. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIf I=E2=80=99=
d have spent the rest of the internship flipping that coin, I=E2=80=99d hav=
e been satisfied.=E2=80=9D And for a while it appeared that he might, as he=
 won the second coin flip too.
I=E2=80=99ll pay a dollar to anyone who will flip me for ninety-nine fifty,=
 shouted Sam.
The other interns clearly felt obligated to take the bets, but the mood in =
the room was shifting in response to Asher=E2=80=99s feelings. =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0But Sam won the third coin flip too, so to his way of thinking the gambl=
ing wasn=E2=80=99t yet over.
I=E2=80=99ll pay a dollar to anyone who=E2=80=99ll flip me for ninety-nine =
seventy-five, he shouted.
It wasn=E2=80=99t until the fourth flip that Sam lost =E2=80=94=C2=A0and by=
 then everyone except Sam was unsettled by Asher=E2=80=99s humiliation.

The point of this story in the book is that Bankman-Fried gets in trouble w=
ith his bosses for being mean to Asher, which he thinks is unfair: =E2=80=
=9CWhat he=E2=80=99d done to Asher was no more than what Jane Street was do=
ing to competitors in financial markets every day.=E2=80=9D
But there are two much weirder things in this anecdote.
First: =E2=80=9CA Jane Street intern had what amounted to a professional ob=
ligation to take any bet with a positive expected value=E2=80=9D? Really? I=
 feel like, if you are a trading intern, you are really there to learn two =
things. One is, sure,=C2=A0take bets with positive expected value and avoid=
 bets with negative expected value.
But the other is about bet=C2=A0sizing. As a Jane Street intern, you have $=
100 to bet each day, and your quasi-job is to turn that into as much money =
as possible. Is betting=C2=A0all of it (or even $98) on a single bet with a=
 1% edge really optimal?
  [6]
=C2=A0
People have thought about this question! Like, this is very much a central =
thing that traders and trading firms worry about. The standard starting poi=
nt is the  Kelly criterion, which computes a maximum bet size=C2=A0based on=
 your edge and the size of your bankroll. Given the intern=E2=80=99s bankro=
ll of $100, I think Kelly would tell you to put=C2=A0at most $10 on this be=
t, depending on what exactly you mean by =E2=80=9Cthis bet.=E2=80=9D
  [7]
 Betting $98 is too much.
I am being imprecise, and for various reasons=C2=A0you might not expect the=
 interns to stick to Kelly in this situation. But when I read about interns=
 lining up to lose their entire bankroll on=C2=A0bets with 1% edge, I think=
, =E2=80=9Chuh, that=E2=80=99s aggressive, what are they teaching those int=
erns?=E2=80=9D (I suppose the $100 daily loss limit is the real lesson abou=
t position sizing: The interns who wipe out today get to come back and play=
 again tomorrow.)=C2=A0
But I also think about a=C2=A0Twitter argument=C2=A0that Bankman-Fried had =
with Matt Hollerbach in 2020, in which Bankman-Fried scoffed=C2=A0at the Ke=
lly criterion and said that=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI, personally, would do more=E2=
=80=9D than the Kelly amount. =E2=80=9CWhy? Because ultimately my utility f=
unction isn=E2=80=99t really logarithmic. It=E2=80=99s closer to linear.=E2=
=80=9D As he tells Lewis, =E2=80=9Che had use for =E2=80=98infinity dollars=
=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0he was going to become a trillionair=
e and use the money to cure disease and align AI and defeat Trump, sure =E2=
=80=94 so he always wanted to maximize returns.
But as Hollerbach pointed out, this misunderstands why trading firms use th=
e Kelly criterion.
  [8]
=C2=A0Jane Street=C2=A0does not go around taking any bet with a positive ex=
pected value. The point of Kelly is not about utility curves; it=E2=80=99s =
not =E2=80=9Chaving $200 is less than=C2=A0twice as pleasant=C2=A0as having=
 $100, so you should be less willing to take big risks for big rewards.=E2=
=80=9D The point of Kelly is about maximizing your chances of surviving and=
 obtaining long-run returns: It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cif you bet 50% of your b=
ankroll on 1%-edge bets, you=E2=80=99ll be more likely to win each bet than=
 lose it, but if you keep doing that you will probably lose all your money =
eventually.=E2=80=9D Kelly is about sizing your bets so you can keep playin=
g the game and make the most money possible in the long run. Betting more c=
an make you more money in the short run, but if you keep doing it you will=
=C2=A0end in ruin.
I don=E2=80=99t know what actually happened at Jane Street that day. I assu=
me that the anecdote in=C2=A0Going Infinite=C2=A0comes from Bankman-Fried. =
=E2=80=9CPeople get so obsessed with free dollars when you frame it correct=
ly,=E2=80=9D he says; he is the one framing this story. What I take from th=
is story, and from other anecdotes here about his early trading career,=C2=
=A0is that Bankman-Fried is good and facile and clever=C2=A0at calculating =
expected value, and at finding ways to inflict pain on counterparties, but =
he is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not even=C2=A0bad=C2=A0at trade sizing; he just doesn=
=E2=80=99t think about it at all. It is not a part of his life. He goes all=
 in on everything.=C2=A0In his model of the world, if you are offered a bet=
 with a 1% edge, you should put all of your money on it, over and over agai=
n, until you lose everything. How will=C2=A0that=C2=A0play out in the secon=
d half of the book?
Here=E2=80=99s the other weird thing about the anecdote: These bets=C2=A0ob=
viously have negative expected value?
Not for his counterparties, who get paid $1 to take a fair coin flip, but f=
or Bankman-Fried. And not the first one; that one is=C2=A0fine; the math ab=
ove is right. He pays $1 to play, he gets a fair coin flip, he makes $33 fr=
om Asher, fine, good trade. But then he keeps going to eke out a few margin=
al pennies from Asher.
  [9]
 When he wins the first flip, Asher owes him $33, the difference between th=
eir $65 strike price and the $98 that the first intern lost. When he wins t=
he second coin flip, Asher owes him an additional=C2=A0one dollar:=C2=A0The=
ir bet is on the=C2=A0maximum=C2=A0loss, not the=C2=A0total=C2=A0loss, so f=
inding another intern to lose $99 increases the payoff by only $1.
  [10]
 The second flip is an even-money proposition for Bankman-Fried: He pays $1=
 to do it and=C2=A0gets an extra $1 from Asher. The third and fourth flips,=
 where he pays $1 to get 50 and then 25 cents from Asher, have=C2=A0negativ=
e expected value. The last flip, which he loses, costs him $100.75 and brin=
gs in nothing.
  [11]

Again, I don=E2=80=99t really know what happened. Perhaps I have misunderst=
ood how the=C2=A0bets worked, or perhaps=C2=A0Lewis did, or perhaps Bankman=
-Fried misremembered, or perhaps he really did get these bets wrong.=C2=A0B=
ut isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0this=C2=A0version of the story revealing? In this sto=
ry:
=09Bankman-Fried found a perfect trade, for him: It was risky but it had a =
lot of edge, it made him look smart, and it made his counterparty look dumb=
.=09He did it, it paid off, he looked smart, his counterparty looked dumb, =
all was right with the world.=09It was so intoxicating to be right that he =
kept doing the trade.=09He never noticed that the trade stopped being good:=
 The glow of being right persisted long after he became wrong.=09Eventually=
 he lost the bet and everyone was mad at him.

Everything about Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s life was perfectly optimized f=
or becoming a famous billionaire and an infamous criminal defendant, in tha=
