<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am about halfway through=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32923785.285424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d25v=
cnRvbi5jb20vYm9va3MvOTc4MTMyNDA3NDMzNQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0778ae3" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"><em>Going Infinite</em></a>, Michael Lewis=E2=80=99 book about Sam B=
ankman-Fried, and I am very much enjoying it. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/32923785.285424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF0aW1lcy5jb20=
vYnVzaW5lc3Mvc3RvcnkvMjAyMy0xMC0wMi90d28tbmV3LWJvb2tzLWNvdmVyLXRoZS1iYW5rbW=
FuLWZyaWVkLWNyeXB0by1zY2FtLW9uZS10ZWxscy10aGUtdHJ1ZS1zdG9yeS10aGUtb3RoZXIta=
XMtYnktbWljaGFlbC1sZXdpcz91dG1fc291cmNlPXN1YnN0YWNrJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWw/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB59cc1316" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Many</a> of the <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32923785.285424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cub=
nl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMy8xMC8wMi9ib29rcy9yZXZpZXcvZ29pbmctaW5maW5pdGUtbWljaGFl=
bC1sZXdpcy5odG1sP3V0bV9zb3VyY2U9c3Vic3RhY2smdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbA/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB34486b8e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> reviews</a> that I have read of the boo=
k complain that Lewis does not sufficiently explain that Bankman-Fried is G=
uilty and Bad, Actually, but that is not the book that he wanted to write o=
r the one I want to read.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> He wanted to understand and explain Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s psychology=
 and tell a good story. If you want to read a moral condemnation of crypto =
theft, you can get that=C2=A0anywhere.=C2=A0You go to Michael Lewis for cha=
racter and=C2=A0story.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, reading those reviews you would think th=
at the book is a defense of Bankman-Fried, but it is actually quite damning=
. (<em>Less=C2=A0</em>damning than most of what is written about Bankman-Fr=
ied these days? Sure.) There is an anecdote (which has been reported before=
) from the early days of Alameda Research, the crypto trading firm that Ban=
kman-Fried started before his crypto exchange FTX, the firm whose trades wi=
th FTX customer money ultimately brought down the whole thing. At some poin=
t Alameda lost track of $4 million of investor money, and the rest of the m=
anagement team was like =E2=80=9Chuh we should tell our investors that we l=
ost their money,=E2=80=9D and Bankman-Fried was like =E2=80=9Cnah it=E2=80=
=99s fine, we=E2=80=99ll probably find it again, let=E2=80=99s just tell th=
em it=E2=80=99s still here.=E2=80=9D The rest of the management team was ho=
rrified and quit in a huff, loudly telling the investors that Bankman-Fried=
 was dishonest and reckless.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then Alameda eventually=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0=
</em>find the money and it was fine. The lesson that Bankman-Fried, and eve=
ryone else who stayed at Alameda, seems to have taken from this episode was=
 something like =E2=80=9CBankman-Fried is infallible, and it=E2=80=99s fine=
 if he takes wild risks and does fraud because it always=C2=A0works out in =
the end.=E2=80=9D I wonder how that approach will play out in the second ha=
lf of the book!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is another strange anecdote from Bankman=
-Fried=E2=80=99s even earlier days, as an intern at Jane Street Capital, th=
e proprietary trading firm.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Jane Street wants to teach its interns to think in bets, so they =
are encouraged to bet against each other all the time. To prevent disaster,=
 there is a rule=C2=A0that no intern can lose more than $100 in a day.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0One morning,=C2=A0another intern, called =E2=80=9CAsher=E2=80=9D =
in the book,=C2=A0offers to bet Bankman-Fried on the maximum amount any int=
ern will lose that day. =E2=80=9CThis cannot settle above one hundred or be=
low zero, right?=E2=80=9D confirms Bankman-Fried. And then he buys at 65: I=
f any intern loses more than $65 that day, Bankman-Fried will pay Asher tha=
t intern=E2=80=99s losses above $65; if none do, Asher will pay Bankman-Fri=
ed the difference between $65 and the maximum loss. If an intern loses $100=
, the maximum, then=C2=A0Bankman-Fried gets $35. If the biggest loser loses=
 only=C2=A0$50, he pays Asher $15.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course Bankman-Fried can easily win this be=
t by=C2=A0<em>losing $100 himself</em>. That is not optimal, for him, but h=
e can use that fact to manufacture a good trade. He immediately turns to th=
e other interns in the room and offers them $1 to take an even-money coin f=
lip for $98.=C2=A0<em>Somebody</em> (Bankman-Fried or his counterparty) wil=
l lose $98 on this bet, so Asher will have to pay him $33 ($98 minus $65).=
=C2=A0If Bankman-Fried=C2=A0wins, he gets $98 (from winning the coin flip),=
 plus $33 (from Asher), minus $1 (he paid the other intern a premium to do =
the coin flip), for a net gain of $130.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If he loses, he loses $98 (coin flip) plus $1 (payment) but gets =
back $33 (Asher), for a net loss of $66.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> That=E2=80=99s a very positive-expected-value bet for him: Bankman-Fri=
ed has a 50/50 chance of winning $130 or losing only $66. But it=E2=80=99s =
also positive-expected-value for his counterparty on the coin flip.=C2=A0Le=
wis writes:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To the Jane Street way of thinking=
, Sam was offering free money. A Jane Street intern had what amounted to a =
professional obligation to take any bet with a positive expected value. The=
 coin toss itself was a 50-50 proposition, and so the expected value to the=
 person who accepted Sam=E2=80=99s bet was a dollar: (0.5 x $98) - (0.5 x $=
98) + $1 =3D $1.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried easily saw how to=C2=A0<em>manuf=
acture=C2=A0</em>the bad outcome for Asher. This is a key skill in trading,=
 but especially in crypto trading. =E2=80=9CAsher was now clearly deeply em=
barrassed.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried finds a taker,=C2=A0wins the coi=
n toss and collects $98 from the other intern. Then he goes again:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To maximize Asher=E2=80=99s pain, some intern =
needed to lose one hundred dollars.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>I=E2=80=99ll pay a dollar to anyone who wi=
ll flip me for ninety-nine dollars,</em> Sam shouted.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now he had a machine for creating wagers in wh=
ich both parties enjoyed positive expected value. That machine was named As=
her. Interns were lined up to take the bet. =E2=80=9CPeople get so obsessed=
 with free dollars when you frame it correctly,=E2=80=9D said Sam. =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIf I=E2=80=99d have spent the rest of the internship flip=
ping that coin, I=E2=80=99d have been satisfied.=E2=80=9D And for a while i=
t appeared that he might, as he won the second coin flip too.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>I=E2=80=99ll pay a dollar to anyone who wi=
ll flip me for ninety-nine fifty</em>, shouted Sam.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other interns clearly felt obligated to ta=
ke the bets, but the mood in the room was shifting in response to Asher=E2=
=80=99s feelings. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0But Sam won the third coin flip too, so to=
 his way of thinking the gambling wasn=E2=80=99t yet over.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>I=E2=80=99ll pay a dollar to anyone who=E2=
=80=99ll flip me for ninety-nine seventy-five</em>, he shouted.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It wasn=E2=80=99t until the fourth flip that S=
am lost =E2=80=94=C2=A0and by then everyone except Sam was unsettled by Ash=
er=E2=80=99s humiliation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point of this story in the book is that Ba=
nkman-Fried gets in trouble with his bosses for being mean to Asher, which =
he thinks is unfair: =E2=80=9CWhat he=E2=80=99d done to Asher was no more t=
han what Jane Street was doing to competitors in financial markets every da=
y.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are two <em>much weirder</em> things=
 in this anecdote.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First: =E2=80=9CA Jane Street intern had what =
amounted to a professional obligation to take any bet with a positive expec=
ted value=E2=80=9D? Really? I feel like, if you are a trading intern, you a=
re really there to learn two things. One is, sure,=C2=A0take bets with posi=
tive expected value and avoid bets with negative expected value.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the other is about bet=C2=A0<em>sizing</em=
>. As a Jane Street intern, you have $100 to bet each day, and your quasi-j=
ob is to turn that into as much money as possible. Is betting=C2=A0<em>all =
of it </em>(or even $98) on a single bet with a 1% edge really optimal?<a c=
lass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People have thought about this question! Like,=
 this is very much a central thing that traders and trading firms worry abo=
ut. The standard starting point is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/32923785.285424/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2=
kvS2VsbHlfY3JpdGVyaW9u/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc6964170" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Kelly cr=
iterion</a>, which computes a maximum bet size=C2=A0based on your edge and =
the size of your bankroll. Given the intern=E2=80=99s bankroll of $100, I t=
hink Kelly would tell you to put=C2=A0at most $10 on this bet, depending on=
 what exactly you mean by =E2=80=9Cthis bet.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> Betting $98 is too much.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am being imprecise, and for various reasons=
=C2=A0you might not expect the interns to stick to Kelly in this situation.=
 But when I read about interns lining up to lose their entire bankroll on=
=C2=A0bets with 1% edge, I think, =E2=80=9Chuh, that=E2=80=99s aggressive, =
what are they teaching those interns?=E2=80=9D (I suppose the $100 daily lo=
ss limit is the real lesson about position sizing: The interns who wipe out=
 today get to come back and play again tomorrow.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I also think about a=C2=A0<a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32923785.285424/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dG=
VyLmNvbS9icmVha2luZ3RoZW1hcmsvc3RhdHVzLzE1OTExMTQzODE1MDg1NTg4NDk/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB220f5235" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Twitter argument</a>=C2=A0that Bankman-Fr=
ied had with Matt Hollerbach in 2020, in which Bankman-Fried scoffed=C2=A0a=
t the Kelly criterion and said that=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI, personally, would do m=
ore=E2=80=9D than the Kelly amount. =E2=80=9CWhy? Because ultimately my uti=
lity function isn=E2=80=99t really logarithmic. It=E2=80=99s closer to line=
ar.=E2=80=9D As he tells Lewis, =E2=80=9Che had use for =E2=80=98infinity d=
ollars=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0he was going to become a trill=
ionaire and use the money to cure disease and align AI and defeat Trump, su=
re =E2=80=94 so he always wanted to maximize returns.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But as Hollerbach pointed out, this misunderst=
ands why trading firms use the Kelly criterion.<a class=3D"footnote-index" =
href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: =
inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0<em>Jane Street=C2=A0</em>does not go around taking any bet with =
a positive expected value. The point of Kelly is not about utility curves; =
it=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=9Chaving $200 is less than=C2=A0twice as pleasant=
=C2=A0as having $100, so you should be less willing to take big risks for b=
ig rewards.=E2=80=9D The point of Kelly is about maximizing your chances of=
 surviving and obtaining long-run returns: It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cif you bet=
 50% of your bankroll on 1%-edge bets, you=E2=80=99ll be more likely to win=
 each bet than lose it, but if you keep doing that you will probably lose a=
ll your money eventually.=E2=80=9D Kelly is about sizing your bets so you c=
an keep playing the game and make the most money possible in the long run. =
Betting more can make you more money in the short run, but if you keep doin=
g it you will=C2=A0end in ruin.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know what actually happened at=
 Jane Street that day. I assume that the anecdote in=C2=A0<em>Going Infinit=
e=C2=A0</em>comes from Bankman-Fried. =E2=80=9CPeople get so obsessed with =
free dollars when you frame it correctly,=E2=80=9D he says; he is the one f=
raming this story. What I take from this story, and from other anecdotes he=
re about his early trading career,=C2=A0is that Bankman-Fried is good and f=
acile and clever=C2=A0at calculating expected value, and at finding ways to=
 inflict pain on counterparties, but he is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not even=C2=A0<em=
>bad=C2=A0</em>at trade sizing; he just doesn=E2=80=99t think about it at a=
ll. It is not a part of his life. He goes all in on everything.=C2=A0In his=
 model of the world, if you are offered a bet with a 1% edge, you should pu=
t all of your money on it, over and over again, until you lose everything. =
How will=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>play out in the second half of the book?</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s the other weird thing about the=
 anecdote: These bets=C2=A0obviously have negative expected value?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not for his counterparties, who get paid $1 to=
 take a fair coin flip, but for Bankman-Fried. And not the first one; that =
one is=C2=A0fine; the math above is right. He pays $1 to play, he gets a fa=
ir coin flip, he makes $33 from Asher, fine, good trade. But then he keeps =
going to eke out a few marginal pennies from Asher.<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a> When he wins the first flip, Asher owes him $33, the difference betwee=
n their $65 strike price and the $98 that the first intern lost. When he wi=
ns the second coin flip, Asher owes him an additional=C2=A0<em>one dollar:=
=C2=A0</em>Their bet is on the=C2=A0<em>maximum</em>=C2=A0loss, not the=C2=
=A0<em>total=C2=A0</em>loss, so finding another intern to lose $99 increase=
s the payoff by only $1.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a> The second flip is an even-money proposition for Bankman-Fried: He pay=
s $1 to do it and=C2=A0gets an extra $1 from Asher. The third and fourth fl=
ips, where he pays $1 to get 50 and then 25 cents from Asher, have=C2=A0neg=
ative expected value. The last flip, which he loses, costs him $100.75 and =
brings in nothing.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-11" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, I don=E2=80=99t really know what happen=
ed. Perhaps I have misunderstood how the=C2=A0bets worked, or perhaps=C2=A0=
Lewis did, or perhaps Bankman-Fried misremembered, or perhaps he really did=
 get these bets wrong.=C2=A0But isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0this<em>=C2=A0</em>versi=
on of the story revealing? In this story:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Bankman-Fried found a perfect trade, =
for him: It was risky but it had a lot of edge, it made him look smart, and=
 it made his counterparty look dumb.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">He did it, it paid off, he looked smart, his counterparty looked dumb, a=
ll was right with the world.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It wa=
s so intoxicating to be right that he kept doing the trade.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He never noticed that the trade stopped being goo=
d: The glow of being right persisted long after he became wrong.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Eventually he lost the bet and everyone was =
mad at him.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everything about Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s l=
ife was perfectly optimized for becoming a famous billionaire and an infamo=
us criminal defendant, in that order.=C2=A0</p>
