<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One psychological difference between stocks an=
d bonds is that people buy stocks largely for capital appreciation and they=
 buy bonds largely for yield. So if you look at a stock and see that it was=
 $10 yesterday and is $15 today, you will think =E2=80=9Cah this stock is g=
ood at appreciating capitally=E2=80=9D and buy it. And if you look at a bon=
d and see that it yielded 4% yesterday and yields 5% today, you will think =
=E2=80=9Cah this bond is getting=C2=A0yieldier=E2=80=9D and buy it. These a=
re somewhat inverse thought processes. (Bond prices move inversely to yield=
s, you know.) Bonds get more attractive as they get cheaper; stocks get mor=
e attractive as they get more expensive.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, I kid, I kid, none of this is totally true=
, and you can always find Warren Buffett or whoever going around like =E2=
=80=9CI love to buy stocks when they are on sale.=E2=80=9D Still as a crude=
 model of retail investor psychology this seems plausible? There are meme s=
tocks, because everyone loves to pile into a stock that has gone up. There =
are not meme bonds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bond yields more or less never went up during =
my lifetime, but now they have, and on this crude model people should be ru=
shing to buy bonds. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/32923785.285424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL3doZW4td2lsbC10aGUtZ=
mVkLXN0b3AtcmFpc2luZy1yYXRlcy10aGF0cy10aGUtdHJpbGxpb24tZG9sbGFyLXF1ZXN0aW9u=
LWZvci1ib25kLWludmVzdG9ycy0yMjA4NmEyMQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdfc143cd" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> And yet</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Asset managers have been counting on what Blac=
kRock calls a =E2=80=9Cgenerational opportunity=E2=80=9D in the bond market=
, now that yields are at decade-plus highs.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors ranging from pension funds to retire=
ment savers should be buying longer-term bonds to lock in higher rates, the=
ir thinking goes, spurring a flood of inflows to bond funds. BlackRock, for=
 one, has projected assets under management at its bond exchange-traded fun=
ds to triple to $2.5 trillion by 2030.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is just one problem: Those flows have ye=
t to materialize. Relentless losses in the bond market have spooked investo=
rs who appear hesitant to jump in until they feel more confident that rates=
 have peaked.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors pulled $78.6 billion from U.S.-based=
 taxable bond funds in the 12 months through August, according to Morningst=
ar. That is well below the nearly $300 billion they pulled from equities ov=
er the same period but a painful sum, regardless, for asset managers hoping=
 for a windfall.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also here=E2=80=99s a good stock-style quote a=
bout bonds being =E2=80=9Con sale=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhen you=E2=80=99re in an=
 environment where bond yields go up every day, it starts getting a little =
nasty,=E2=80=9D said Steve Sosnick, chief strategist at Interactive Brokers=
. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t see people rushing in to buy bonds right now jus=
t because they=E2=80=99re kind of a falling knife. They=E2=80=99re on sale =
and lower prices should create demand, but we=E2=80=99re not seeing that.=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
