endorse. Faux=E2=80=99s book is great, and hilarious, and morally scathing,=
 and also way more skeptical about crypto and Bankman-Fried than Lewis is.<=
/p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-2" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[2] An awkward aspect of this book is that, wi=
th Bankman-Fried as the protagonist and Jane Street as his formative tradin=
g experience, Lewis portrays Jane Street in a very admiring way. But of cou=
rse Lewis <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32923785=
.285424/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvRmxhc2hfQm95cw/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB7ca7b31b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">also wrote =E2=80=9CFlash Boys.=E2=80=9D</a>=
 This necessitates a funny footnote on page 64, in which Lewis basically sa=
ys =E2=80=9CI know that I wrote a whole book where the premise was that hig=
h-frequency traders are Bad, but for purposes of *this* book they are Good.=
=E2=80=9D (Or, at least, those *other* HFT firms are Bad, but Jane Street i=
s Good.)</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] I assume that this is operationalized as l=
ike =E2=80=9Cyou cannot have more than $100 of independent exposure out at =
one time, and if you have lost $X in a day then you can=E2=80=99t have more=
 than $(100 - X) of exposure out for the rest of the day.=E2=80=9D Note tha=
t in the anecdote we are going to discuss, Bankman-Fried has $65 of exposur=
e on his initial bet and $98 of exposure on his coin flip, both of them unr=
esolved, but of course they are not independent: If he wins *or* loses the =
coin flip, he wins $33 on his initial bet; there is no way for him to lose =
both bets. There=E2=80=99s, like, a portfolio margining concept for the int=
ern bets.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] That is how Lewis does the math. I think t=
echnically the other intern lost $97, though? He lost $98 on the flip but g=
ot paid $1 to take it, so his net payoff is negative $97? So Asher should p=
ay Bankman-Fried $32? It depends on whether you think the $1 payment is par=
t of the bet, but I think it clearly is.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-5" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[5] Again I think technically Bankman-Fried ha=
s lost $99 so the side bet should pay $34, but whatever. Also I suppose the=
re is an argument that you should net the $33 (or $34) from Asher against h=
is losses here, leaving him with losses of only $65, and thus making Asher =
the winner of the bet? But if you do that then he doesn't have the $33, so =
his losses are $98, so he does win the bet? Very paradoxical.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-6" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[6] I am being a little inaccurate here, becau=
se $100 is not *really* the intern=E2=80=99s entire bankroll. Jane Street i=
nterns are well paid and can probably afford to lose $100 in a day, and if =
they do then they can come back tomorrow with a fresh $100. Your job is to =
maximize returns (or learning, or whatever) over the whole summer, not over=
 any one day. So it is plausible to think that your $100 is, you know, 1/60=
th of your bankroll or whatever, and so it=E2=80=99s not so bad to bet $100=
 on a 1%-edge bet. (It is more than Kelly however.) If you do that each day=
, you will in expectation end up with a profit of $60 for the summer. (You =
win $101 30 times, and you lose $99 30 times.) That=E2=80=99s =E2=80=A6 not=
 =E2=80=A6 great? </p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-7" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[7] I am taking some liberties here in specify=
ing what the bet is. What I mean in the text is: If you are offered a flat =
$1 to take an even-money coin-flip bet, and your bankroll is $100, and you =
can set the size of the bet, then $10 is the number that roughly works in t=
he Kelly math. The Kelly proportion of your bankroll to bet is (probability=
 of win - (probability of loss / payoff)), where =E2=80=9Cpayoff=E2=80=9D i=
s the proportion of the bet that you get back on a win (even money is 1.0).=
 With a $10 bet, you lose $9 if you lose and win $11 if you win (due to the=
 extra dollar payment), making this =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D a $9 bet from =
your perspective, and (0.5 - (0.5/(11/9)) =3D 0.09, and 9% of your bankroll=
 is $9 (which is a $10 bet with the extra $1). This is counterfactual, thou=
gh; Bankman-Fried did not offer $1 to bet $10, and there are other ways to =
specify the counterfactual bet. If you just do Kelly on like =E2=80=9Ccoin =
flip with 1% edge=E2=80=9D (that is, 50.5% chance of winning 100% and 49.5%=
 chance of losing 100%), it would tell you to bet 1% of your bankroll, or $=
1.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-8" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[8] Here is a blog post with more about Bankma=
n-Fried=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
32923785.285424/aHR0cHM6Ly9xb3BwYWMuYmxvZ3Nwb3QuY29tLzIwMjIvMTEvaWYteW91cmU=
tc28tc21hcnQtaG93LWNvbWUteW91cmUtbm90Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBff9ea=
993" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">odd interpretation of bet sizing</a>. =E2=80=9CWith Kelly we a=
ren't really making any assumptions about utility function: our assumption =
is effectively that the median is the correct expectations operator.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-9" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[9] Why did he not just start with a $100 bet?=
 (Or $99, I guess, if his $1 payment counts against his own maximum loss.)<=
/p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-10" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ita=
lic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[10] Also, what if Bankman-Fried loses that to=
ss? He goes from positive $98 from the first flip to negative $1 after the =
second, or really negative $3 if you include the premiums he paid. He's not=
 the biggest loser; the biggest loser is still the guy who lost $98. So Ash=
er doesn't owe him any more money.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-11" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ita=
lic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[11] See the previous footnote: Asher doesn't =
owe him the extra 25 cents because he's still up on the day. Actually he's =
still up a lot, and it is plausible that his utility curve was such that a =
chance of inflicting 25 cents more pain on Asher was worth losing $100.75 o=
f house money for him. But! That=E2=80=99s weird!</p>
</div>
